                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-defend2092" type="age" value="41"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18280911-390-off2028" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-off2028" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-off2028" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18280911-390-cd2029" type="crimeDate">8th of July</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-390-off2028 t18280911-390-cd2029"></join>, 4 lbs. weight of bacon, value 2s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               <persName id="t18280911-390-victim2093" type="victimName">
                  William 
                  Softley
               <interp inst="t18280911-390-victim2093" type="surname" value="Softley"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-victim2093" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-victim2093" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-390-off2028 t18280911-390-victim2093"></join>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>WILLIAM SOFTLEY. I am a <rs id="t18280911-390-viclabel2030" type="occupation">cheesemonger</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-390-victim2093 t18280911-390-viclabel2030"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18280911-390-crimeloc2031">Old Brentford</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-390-crimeloc2031" type="placeName" value="Old Brentford"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-390-crimeloc2031" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-390-off2028 t18280911-390-crimeloc2031"></join>. On the 8th of July, between nine and ten o'clock in the morning, I was at the door putting some goods into the cart, and when I returned I missed a piece of bacon - I saw it again in ten minutes under the prisoner's coat; I knew him before, but he was not in my employ; he had not left the shop; I took it from him; when I first asked him, he said he had not got it - I asked him again, he denied it; I opened his coat and took it from there.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BODKIN. Q. Did he not say anything about it? A. No; he said he wanted 1 oz. of tea, and he put down a shilling to pay for the tea - the bacon was not in his hand; his coat was buttoned, and his hand against it; he did not put the bacon on the counter and the money to pay for it - I did not put it under his coat again, and call my man to see where it was, and say,"Now you can swear you saw it under his coat;" my man came before the bacon was put down at all; I served him with the tea, and then charged him with the bacon - he did not say he had no notion of taking it without paying for it - but he said afterwards, he would do anything if I would forgive him, he did not offer to pay for it till I found it on him - he then said he did it for want.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-390-person2094">
                  HENRY 
                  LINKFORD
               <interp inst="t18280911-390-person2094" type="surname" value="LINKFORD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-person2094" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-person2094" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , I am in the prosecutor's employ. I saw the prisoner come into the shop as I was putting some bacon into the cart; I went into the shop just after he was served with the tea - my master said, "What have you got under your coat?" he said, Nothing; my master said, "You must have something, let me see what;" I forced his coat open, and there was this piece of bacon; my master told us to fetch a constable - he said he would do anything if he would forgive him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-390-person2095">
                  JOSEPH 
                  DICKINSON
               <interp inst="t18280911-390-person2095" type="surname" value="DICKINSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-person2095" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-person2095" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I went to the shop, and saw the prisoner in the prosecutor's parlour - I knew him, and said, "I am very sorry to see you here Lane;" he denied his name several times, but I knew him very well; I said to the prosecutor, "What is your intention;" he said, "I give you charge of him, take him to a Magistrate;" the prisoner then went on his knees and begged for mercy, and said, "You don't know my circumstances;" I found near 16l. on him.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I saw a piece of bacon which I thought would suit my family; I took it up and put it under my arm; I then had some tea, and paid for it; the prosecutor said, "What have you got here?" I said, "A piece of bacon, which I intend to pay you for;" I put it on the counter and half a crown to pay for it - he then took it up, put it under my coat, and called the man, and said,"Now you can swear."</p>
               <p>MR. HENRY HAINES. I am an auctioneer and appraiser,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182809110179"></xptr>and live in Fore-street. I have known the prisoner more than twenty years - I have had several transactions with him to a considerable amount, and during that time he has always conducted himself in an honest and proper manner; he has seven children, and his wife is now pregnant.</p>
               <p>MR. BODKIN to MR. SOFTLEY. Q. Did you say to Mr. Haines that it would be a great injury if you did not convict this man? A. No; I said it would be a great injury if I did not appear against him; he wrote to me, wanting me to make a flaw in the indictment.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Did you say, that in consequence of some letter written by somebody? A. Yes, because they wanted me not to appear; Mr. Haines came to my place, and began a conversation on the subject of this prosecution - the letter came by post from the prisoner.</p>
               <p>MR. BODKIN to MR. HAINES. Q. Do you remember going to the prosecutor's? A. Yes, and he said to me, that it would be a great injury, if he did not succeed in convicting the prisoner.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Are you sure those were the words he used? A. Yes; I went to him and he said, it was his duty to prosecute, but in consequence of his family, I hoped he would be as lenient as he could; I was very cautious in my expression - this was about ten days ago.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280911-390-verdict2032" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18280911-390-verdict2032" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 41.</p>
